    "summary": "New Testament studies and Early Christianity are my passions. Questions and problems about religion today are rooted in our history. I help understanding the origins of these questions and problems, and want to do this especially in my PhD-project at Tilburg University.\n\nCurrent research topics and expertise:\n- \"Cross-bearing\" in Antiquity\n- Early Christian (radicalist) interpretations\n- 3 John\n\nBesides these subjects, I am working on my PhD project called: \"Martyrdom and Metaphor: A Semiotic Perspective on Early Christian Cross-bearing Traditions\"\n\nTo give yourself freely to be executed on a torture device is something extremely radical, and Jesus\u2019 call to carry one\u2019s cross was often interpreted martyriologically, especially in antiquity. Yet his call has also been interpreted as a metaphor for a variety of things, like renouncing oneself, accepting ilness or whatever kind of suffering. But what happens exactly between text and reader in the interpretation of Jesus' call to bear one's cross? In my PhD I look at the first four centuries to see how writers and thinkers have interpreted Jesus' cross-bearing saying. I trace back the interpretation processes they made, to give insight in how on the one hand martyriological interpretations and mitigating ones on the other end are formed. This gives insight in interpretational processes in general and the reception history of \u201ccross-bearing\u201d in particular.",
